In fact, cases of divorce in Colombia are on the rise whereas U.S. divorce rates are dropping in that age group.

Women over 45 in the United States are twice as likely to initiate a divorce as than their unmarried counterparts, and when the divorce does occur, the woman “won’t be afraid of going back to school and reinventing herself,” she said, compared to a divorcée who will be more likely to stay where she is financially, which gives her more freedom in the marriage.

Here are some other things I learned from his magazine and this class by Nivedita in our Stanford GSB MBA program:

Couples with sororal polygyny (i.e. when two (or more) women marry one man) tend to divorce more affluently and are less likely to return to the same type of relationship than those married by a non-sororal polygyny.

Despite the negative objective outcomes, marriage may trigger important choices that lead to change and to more thorough evaluations.

Regarding women who faced discrimination, sororal polygyny actually increased their well-being—especially in the two-mom group.

When modeling stress and happiness, women who were sororally married were more happy than those who were monogamously married.

Sororal polygyny made women feel more loved than monogamous marriage.
